  

<h2 id="everything-will-one-day-pass-so-im-not-going-to-sweat-what-i-dont-need-to">Everything will one day pass, so I‚Äôm not going to sweat what I don‚Äôt need to</h2>
<p>I write in open formats to avoid app lock-in, but don‚Äôt particularly care if they survive me. Here are some thoughts on the topic of longevity vs convenience in the plain text world.</p>
<h3 id="the-openest-of-open-formats">The openest of open formats</h3>
<p>Files in an open format can be read on (almost) any device without losing their core function and without requiring proprietary or closed source apps. Text can still be read, links between notes are still be clickable, images can still be viewed as intended on any device.</p>
<p>According to my understanding the only format that <em>really</em> ticks these boxes is <span class="small-caps">HTML</span>, the ubiquitous web language that can do all that and so much more.</p>
<p>I regularly remind myself that while some note formats are more open than others, some of those others are <em>open enough</em> for my needs.</p>
<p>There was a <a href="https://union.place/@publicvoit@graz.social/114229465591055307" target="_blank">thought provoking discussion</a> on Mastodon recently, on what the <em>best</em> format for note making might be.</p>
<p>Karl Voit:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>re-evaluate your requirements and switch to a much better long-term alternative, such as Emacs Orgmode &amp; not yet another hip lock-in monster like Obsidian (<a href="https://karl-voit.at/2021/01/18/tool-choices/" target="_blank">read more from Karl on how to choose a tool</a>)</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Feral Thoughts:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>local websites is what these software should produce as output‚Äîallowing any browser on any platform to open them. That will ensure meaningful possession and ownership of data over the long term.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Me:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I‚Äôm confident in not being locked in to Obsidian because I regularly use my files in other apps. They work just fine. E.g. iA Writer, Notenik, Tangent. It‚Äôs also not hard to mass convert wiki links to Markdown link format.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>‚Ä¶And I‚Äôd add, it‚Äôs surely not hard to mass convert wiki links to <span class="small-caps">HTML</span>.</p>
<p>Despite the devoted following org mode inspires, I took one (or two or three) look(s) and ran away screaming.</p>
<p>Org isn‚Äôt like cilantro (the herb from hell), but maybe it‚Äôs like onions? I couldn‚Äôt tolerate onions for the first 20 years of my life, while today I can happily eat them raw as a condiment if sliced thinly enough. (In case there‚Äôs some latent symbolism here, may the record state that I enjoy the taste of coriander seed, just not the green leafy bits that sprout from it.)</p>
<p>My fear is that org for me would be more like Turkish Delight, as I have <a href="https://narnia.fandom.com/wiki/Turkish_Delight" target="_blank">Edmund</a>-ish tendencies and might not know when to call enough, enough!</p>
<h3 id="markdown-my-non-standardised-friend">Markdown ‚Äî my non-standardised friend</h3>
<p>I‚Äôve read some diverse takes on Markdown recently. From <a href="https://www.adamhyde.net/whats-wrong-with-markdown/" target="_blank">Adam Hyde</a> calling it<span class="push-double"></span> <span class="pull-double">‚Äú</span>a text format that lazy people use to write <span class="small-caps">HTML</span><span class="push-double"></span><span class="pull-double">‚Äù</span>, to <a href="https://hbowie.net/writings/why-i-use-markdown-and-why-you-should-too.html" target="_blank">Herb Bowie</a> (Notenik) and <a href="https://ia.net/topics/markdown-and-the-slow-fade-of-the-formatting-fetish" target="_blank">Oliver Reichenstein</a> (iA Writer), who promote its use.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>To write well, you only need to know how to make paragraphs and headings. The rest can wait. The flavor of Markdown or markup you use doesn‚Äôt matter. What matters is focusing on your words and their structure. ‚ÄîOliver Reichenstein</p>
</blockquote>
<p>And so I continue to stick with Markdown, despite the facts that it‚Äôs not standardised and that some people think it‚Äôs a bad idea. I‚Äôve heard the pros and cons and choose it anyway, because it meets both my current and projected needs.</p>
<h3 id="avoid-lock-in-sure-but-above-all-have-fun">Avoid lock-in, sure, but above all have fun</h3>
<p>The key to avoiding plain text app lock-in is this: don‚Äôt rely on features available only in one app. If your notes work okay in several different Markdown apps (or would, with bulk edits) and at least one of those apps is open source, why worry?</p>
<p>If org mode or <span class="small-caps">HTML</span> notes are your jam, all good. Enjoy.</p>
<p>I‚Äôve spent too long worrying about the long-term accessibility and readability of my notes. It‚Äôs time to focus on what these notes are for, and, more importantly, who they‚Äôre helping me to become. I still dream of making a <a href="https://ellanew.com/ptpl/071-file-based-knowledge-management">file-based knowledge management system</a> viable on iOS[^1], but until then, what I can access on both my laptop (MacBook Pro) and portable devices (iPhone and iPad) will do very nicely. One more thing: do print out your most important notes and store them carefully. <a href="https://ellanew.com/2022-06-08-paperless-no-legacy">Here‚Äôs why</a>.</p>
<h2 id="semi-breaking-news">Semi-Breaking News:</h2>
<p>Hookmark will be available on iOS later this year, <a href="https://cogzest.com/2025/03/unbelievable/" target="_blank">says Luc Beaudoin</a>!</p>
<hr>
<p>[^1] Until something changes and iOS devices allow the full name of files to be displayed in file lists, this dream is a distant reality. I want to see the maximum number of characters displayed on multiple lines, please! Before you suggest apps for me to try, be aware that I‚Äôve pretty much tried them all. That said, if you‚Äôve found one that really-truly can display multi-line file names in the file picker, let me know!! The only iOS app I know of is Obsidian, and then only when you tweak the Minimal Theme settings. If Kepano can do it surely someone else can, too, right??</p>
